 Wales","Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1310–5 October 1356":"1310–5 October 1356","1310–1356":"1310–1356","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1312–Female":"1312–Deceased","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1283–Male":"1283–Deceased","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","1315":"1315","5 October 1356":"5 October 1356","1312":"1312","1356":"1356","1310":"1310","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: traditional spelling of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘ardour’; borne in the Middle Ages by various rulers in south-west Wales, including  Rhys ap Tewdur  (  d. 1093 ) and  Rhys ap Gruffudd  (  1132–97 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Reece","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Rhys . The name is now in widespread and frequent use outside Wales, in many cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the given name."]},{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Welsh Rhys, in some cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the Welsh given name."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rhys ap Gruffudd was born in 1310, in Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Gruffudd ap Rhys, was 28 and his mother, Gwerful ferch Watkin, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Elsbeth verch Dafydd. He died on 5 October 1356, in Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1310–5 October 1356":"1310–5. oktoober 1356","1310–1356":"1310–1356","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1283–Male":"1283–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1315":"1315","5 October 1356":"5. oktoober 1356","1312":"1312","1356":"1356","1310":"1310","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1310–5 October 1356":"1310–5. lokakuuta 1356","1310–1356":"1310–1356","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1283–Male":"1283–Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1315":"1315","5 October 1356":"5. lokakuuta 1356","1312":"1312","1356":"1356","1310":"1310","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1310–5 October 1356":"1310–5 octobre 1356","1310–1356":"1310–1356","1315–Male":"1315–Décédé","1312–Female":"1312–Décédée","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1283–Male":"1283–Décédé","1290–Female":"1290–Décédée","1315":"1315","5 October 1356":"5 octobre 1356","1312":"1312","1356":"1356","1310":"1310","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1290":"1290","Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Galles","Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales":